              <h2>How this closing costs calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates typical closing costs for both buyers and
                sellers based on your home price, down payment, loan type, and
                state tax environment. It is designed for fast planning and
                “what‑if” scenarios, not to replace your official Loan Estimate
                or Closing Disclosure.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Core formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Loan amount</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Loan amount} = \text{Purchase price} \times \left(1 -
                  \frac{\text{Down payment \%}}{100}\right) \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Buyer closing costs</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Buyer costs} = \text{Purchase price} \times
                  \frac{\text{Buyer cost \%}}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Seller closing costs</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Seller costs} = \text{Sale price} \times
                  \frac{\text{Seller cost \%}}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Monthly principal &amp; interest payment</strong>
                  (standard mortgage formula)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ M = P \times \frac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \] where \(P\) is
                  the loan amount, \(r\) is the monthly interest rate, and \(n\)
                  is the number of monthly payments.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. What counts as buyer closing costs?</h3>
              <p>Typical buyer closing costs include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Lender &amp; origination fees</strong> – underwriting,
                  processing, points, application fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Title, escrow &amp; recording</strong> – title search,
                  lender’s title insurance, settlement/escrow fee, recording
                  fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Prepaids &amp; escrows</strong> – prepaid interest,
                  initial deposits for property taxes and homeowners insurance,
                  sometimes HOA dues.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Third‑party services</strong> – appraisal, inspection,
                  survey, pest inspection, etc.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In many markets, this totals around
                <strong>2%–5% of the purchase price</strong> for buyers. FHA and
                VA loans can shift how some fees are paid, but the overall range
                is similar.
              </p>

              <h3>3. What counts as seller closing costs?</h3>
              <p>Sellers usually pay:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Real estate commissions</strong> – often 4%–7% of the
                  sale price, depending on your listing agreement and local
                  norms.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Transfer taxes &amp; government fees</strong> – state,
                  county, or city transfer taxes, plus recording fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Seller credits</strong> – if you agree to pay part of
                  the buyer’s closing costs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Other seller fees</strong> – attorney fees (in
                  attorney states), HOA transfer fees, home warranty, etc.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                All in, seller closing costs commonly land around
                <strong>6%–10% of the sale price</strong>, dominated by
                commissions.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Rolling closing costs into the loan</h3>
              <p>When you choose “Roll into the loan,” the calculator:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Adds estimated buyer closing costs (minus any seller credit)
                  to the loan amount.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Recalculates your monthly principal &amp; interest payment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Shows the difference vs. paying costs out of pocket at
                  closing.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Not all loan programs or lenders allow every fee to be financed,
                and there are maximum loan‑to‑value (LTV) limits. Use this as a
                planning tool and confirm details with your lender.
              </p>

              <h2>Tips for reducing closing costs</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Shop multiple lenders.</strong> Compare origination
                  fees, points, and third‑party costs on standardized Loan
                  Estimates.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ask about lender credits.</strong> A slightly higher
                  interest rate can sometimes reduce or eliminate upfront costs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Negotiate seller credits.</strong> In a buyer’s
                  market, sellers may agree to cover part of your closing costs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Time your closing date.</strong> Closing near the end
                  of the month can reduce prepaid interest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Review optional add‑ons.</strong> Home warranties,
                  “junk” fees, and some services may be negotiable or optional.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations & disclaimers</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator provides
                <strong>general educational estimates</strong> based on common
                U.S. mortgage practices and public guidance from organizations
                like the CFPB, Fannie Mae, and Freddie Mac. Actual closing costs
                depend on your specific property, lender, title company, state
                and local laws, and contract terms.
              </p>
              <p>
                Always rely on your official
                <strong>Loan Estimate (LE)</strong> and
                <strong>Closing Disclosure (CD)</strong>, and consult a licensed
                loan officer, real estate agent, or attorney for advice about
                your transaction.
              </p>
            </section>
